UPDATE  `node_revisions` SET `body` = '<dl class="portlet toc" id="document-toc"><ol><li><a href="#section-0">What is semantic interoperability ?<br /></a></li><li><a href="#section-1">Guidelines and studies<br /></a></li><li><a href="#section-2">Publications</a></li><li><a href="#section-3">Code Person<br /></a></li><li><a href="#section-4">Code lists<br /></a></li><li><a href="#section-5">Taxonomies</a></li><li><a href="#section-6">Video Tutorials<br /></a></li></ol><a name="section-0"></a></dl><h3>What is semantic interoperability ?</h3><p>In its reference document, the \'European Interoperability Framework\', the European Commission defines interoperability as the ability of information and communication technology (ICT) systems and the business processes they support to exchange data and to enable the sharing of information and knowledge: \'Semantic Interoperability enables systems to combine received information with other information resources and to process it in a meaningful manner\' . It aims at the mental representations that human beings have of the meaning of any given data.&nbsp;</p><p><a href="practice_aids/what-semantic-interoperability">To know more about semantic interoperability.</a><a name="section-1"></a></p><h3>Guidelines and studies</h3><p>Joinup is producing guidelines and studies related to questions of semantic interoperability.&nbsp;</p><p><a href="practice_aids/guidelines-and-studies">You can download these publications here</a>.<br /><a name="section-2"></a></p><h3>Publications</h3><p>Joinup and its partners inform about their work and current developments in a number of articles and documents.&nbsp;<br /><br />You can download these external publications here.<a name="section-3"></a></p><h3>Core Person</h3><p>As a shared development activity, Joinup and more than 100 of its users have developed a data model for persons that is supposed to be used as a core element for any person-related data exchange in eGovernment projects and public administration in Europe. It is supposed to become the first-ever conformant interoperability asset. Other core concepts will follow.</p><p><a href="practice_aids/core-person">To know more about Core Person</a>.<a name="section-4"></a></p><h3>Code lists</h3><p>In many occasions code lists are used as a major key to interoperability. It is a very economic approach to achieve seamless data exchange across language or domain borders. Joinup outlines its action plan for code lists.</p><p><a href="practice_aids/code-lists">To know more about code lists</a>.<a name="section-6"></a></p><h3>Taxonomies</h3><p>Another focus topic of Joinup, taxonomies are assessed for their potential to create or jeopardise interoperability.</p><p><a href="practice_aids/taxonomies">To know more about taxonomies</a>.<a name="section-7"></a></p><h3>Video Tutorials</h3><p>In cooperation with our partner Videolectures.net we present online lectures and tutorials on semantic interoperability, ontology engineering and related issues.</p><p><a href="practice_aids/video-tutorials">To know more about video tutorials</a>.</p>' WHERE `node_revisions`.`nid` =2556 LIMIT 1;

